TI  - Response of Axonopus catarinensisand Arachis pintoito shade conditions.
T2  - Tropical Grasslands - Forrajes Tropicales
M3  - Journal article
M3  - Conference paper
AB  - A study was conducted in Argentina to quantify the dry matter (DM) yield and nutritive quality of Axonopus catarinensisand Arachis pintoiunder different levels of shade (0, 38, 53 and 71%) for silvopastoral use. Shade had an effect on both Axonopus catarinensisand Arachis pintoiyields over the experimental period (390 days). The increased DM production in Axonopus catarinensiswith 38% shade was due to the high rate of growth achieved from the beginning of spring until the start of drought in summer, when plant available soil water did not limit growth. The shade treatments did not have a significant effect on cell wall components in either species. Overall, under shade, concentrations of Cu and Fe increased in both species, suggesting increased uptake of these elements in the shaded area, and K and Zn concentrations increased in the grass. There was a significant increase from 9.1 to 12.6% in protein concentration in Axonopus catarinensiswith shade but no response in Arachis pintoi(average of 22.4%). It is concluded that both species showed good performance under intermediate levels of shade, and thus are promising for use in silvopastoral systems.
