TI  - Minor fruits in Bangladesh: nutrition, food security, economy, women's participation and poverty reduction.
T2  - Proceedings of the International Symposium on Minor Fruits and Medicinal Plants for Health and Ecological Security (ISMF & MP), West Bengal, India, 19-22 December, 2011
M3  - Book chapter
M3  - Conference paper
AB  - Improved varieties of indigenous minor fruits are available in Bangladesh. The paper deals with achievements, constraints and opportunities of minor fruit crops in Bangladesh. Huge numbers of tribal peoples are dependant on the minor fruits. Minor fruits also contribute significantly in herbal medicine. Minor fruit trees like river ebony, velvet apple, cowa, jujube are contributing to protect from natural disaster and balancing the coastal ecosystem. Contribution of the fruits in the nutrition of poor people and to alleviate poverty in coastal, hunger prone (monga) and flood affected areas is also addressed. Plantation of minor fruit ber (Jujube) cv. BAU Kul 1 tremendously contributes in the poverty reduction and natural soil reclamation from saline to non-saline condition in the coastal areas of Bangladesh. Almost every year Bangladesh is facing serious flood and other natural disasters in about one third of the area where serious food shortage, nutrition problems, poverty enhancement happen. Similarly, in the extreme northern part of the country (about one tenth to the country area) periodic serious food crisis due to shortage of employment, no crops harvest at that time causes disaster popularly known as Monga (hunger prone).
