TY  - JOUR
AU  - Goshme, Shenkute
TI  - The impact of community-based breeding programs on indigenous breed genetic improvement and farmers' livelihoods in Ethiopia: a case study.
T2  - Animal Science Cases
M3  - Case study
AB  - Community-based breeding programs (CBBPs) offer a hands-on, locally driven approach to improving the genetics of indigenous livestock in Ethiopia. Unlike traditional crossbreeding or centralised breeding schemes, CBBPs actively involve farmers in the process, making them more effective and sustainable. This study reviews the impact of these programs in three key regions, Menz, Bonga, and Horro, focusing mainly on sheep and goats, with some emerging work on cattle. Drawing from peer-reviewed research, reports from ICARDA and ILRI, and field observations, the findings show clear genetic improvements: sheep saw a 20% increase in body weight and lambing rates, while goats improved kidding rates by up to 15%. Crucially, these gains were achieved without losing valuable traits like disease resistance and drought tolerance. Beyond genetics, the programs also delivered strong socio-economic benefits. Household incomes rose by 20-30%, mutton consumption increased by 15%, and farmers gained better market access through 35 cooperatives. Importantly, women and youth also found more opportunities to participate. However, challenges remain, including difficulties with tracking animal pedigrees, infrastructure gaps, risks of inbreeding, and limited funding. The study highlights the potential of CBBPs to sustainably improve both animal genetics and rural livelihoods and recommends more investment in digital tools, farmer training, and strategies tailored to different regions to help scale up their impact.
