TI  - Impact of the effluents from fish processing industries on water body of aquaculture in Jabusha beel, Khulna District.
T2  - Journal of Subtropical Agricultural Research and Development
M3  - Journal article
AB  - Jabusha beel Flood Control and Drainage (FCD) sub-project has been running from 1996-1997 as first-phase under Local Government Engineering Department (LGED), Bangladesh. At present, the sub-project is passing through time for discharging effluents from recently established fish processing industries. Processed fishery commodity is increasing rapidly due to the steady increase in the total fishery production. Processing of large bulk of fish and shrimp produces a corresponding large bulk of wastes. This study was conducted to identify the impact of the effluent from fish processing industries on the water body of aquaculture of Jabusha beel, Khulna District during 2005. Fish and shrimp processing effluents are very high in biological oxygen demand (BOD), chemical oxygen demand (COD), chloride (Cl-), phosphate (PO4-3), ammonia, organic matters and nutrients. Processing plants produce heavy loads of wastes that are complex mixtures of many substances particularly nitrogen and phosphorus and many others. In comparison with the standard water chemistry for aquaculture, the effluent contains high concentration of ammonia, phosphate and alkalinity. Fish and shrimp processing effluents are, therefore, highly likely to produce adverse effects on beel water environment. Fish species are feeding in contaminated water and are subject to mass mortality. However, application of simple treatment options such as screening can substantially reduce the waste loads.
