TY  - JOUR
AU  - Nesar Ahmed, Nesar Ahmed
TI  - Potential of urban aquaculture in Mymensingh, Bangladesh.
T2  - Fish Farmer
M3  - Journal article
AB  - This article presents a preliminary study carried out through Participatory Community Appraisal in Mashkanda, a suburb 3 km away from Mymensingh City in Bangladesh, on urban aquaculture. The fish are cultured semi-intensively on a small-scale. Most producers stock a polyculture of sarputi, common carp, grass carp and Indian major carps. The farmers also add other species such as tilapia and pangus. The average stocking density is 18500 fingerlings/ha. The culture period is around 6 months. Commercially manufactured pelleted feeds are used by all respondents. A small number of farmers use fertilizers for grow-out of fish. The average annual fish yield is 2500 kg/ha. Fish are harvested by a group of commercial harvesters who earn daily wages of about $2.14. Of the fish harvested, 60 and 40% are sold directly to local consumers on the farm site and to retail markets, respectively. The price of fish depends on the species, quality, size, weight, supply, demand and taste. Some of the constraints for urban aquaculture are discussed (water pollution, urbanization, improper infrastructure, floods and high labour wage rates). Considering the recent development of urban aquaculture in Mymensingh, it is difficult to conclude a positive note for its sustainability.
