T2  - Economic and Political Weekly
M3  - Journal article
AB  - This article examines the effectiveness of the state's response, with respect to shelter and settlement strategies adopted in containing the disaster impact of the December 2004 tsunami in Tamil Nadu, India on particular fishing communities. A study was carried out in three of the most affected districts of the state i.e. Cuddalore, Nagapattinam and Kanyakumari, in two phases, May 2005 and November 2007. With respect to housing, it is argued that the tsunami relief effort has woefully fallen short of the goal. Even three years after the disaster, a large proportion of the affected continue to live in temporary shelters or in inadequate "permanent" houses. If the family chose to reside in their original habitation, they were compelled to generate their own funds for construction as they could not avail of government relief measures. Under the new coastal zone management rules in 2007, there is no guarantee of traditional rights to fisher communities over the use of coastal land so that the government can use it for commercial purposes. In conclusion, the mass displacement and the subsequent new settlement strategies have created an opportunity for the state to administer, manage and restructure land and property rights which has resulted in the dislocation of the fishing communities from their traditional land posing a serious threat to their livelihood and well-being.
