TI  - Influence of age, sex and season on the mortality of crossbred calves.
T2  - Indian Journal of Veterinary Medicine
M3  - Journal article
AB  - Data were collected from the Instructional Dairy Farm (IDF) of G.B. Pant University of Agriculture and Technology in Pantnagar, Uttaranchal, India from 1993 to 2002 and calf mortality was analysed based on age, sex and season. The mortalities were studied up to one year of age in 9 age groups: 0-7, 8-15, 16-30, 31-60, 61-90, 91-120, 121-150, 151-180 days and 181 days to one year. Chi-square test was applied to study the differences in mortality rates among different age groups, sex and season. A total of 1684 calves were born during the period (1993-2002) and of these, 650 calves died. Overall calf mortality was 38.59%. Mortality for male and female calves was 40.90 and 36.29%, respectively. There was no significant difference between sex. Among the different age groups, the highest mortality was recorded in the 121-150 days age group (5.99%), followed by 91-120 days age group (5.23%). No significant difference among age groups was found. The highest mortality (90.15%) was observed during the rainy season (August-October) followed by summer (36.74%, May-July), winter (30.46%, November-January) and autumn (18.33%, February-April). A significant difference was found among seasons. The high mortality during the rainy season may be due to increased dampness and unsanitary conditions due to heavy rainfall over a short period of time.
