TI  - Relative importance and effective utilization of water resources for fish farming in Upper Krishna basin of Maharashtra: a spatio and temporal analysis.
T2  - Indian Journal of Regional Science
M3  - Journal article
AB  - This study aims at the analysis of the relative importance and effective utilization of water resources for fish farming activity in Upper Krishna basin of Maharashtra. The relative importance of inland water resources are computed against total geographical area of the region by using Greboval, Bellemans and Fryd's method. The effective utilization of inland water area is calculated by Agrawal's method. The analysis reveals that, the Krishna basin, one of the well watered and relatively developed parts of the state, is characterised by the variations in physico-socio-economic aspects which have influenced the inland fish farming activity of the region. As such the tahsils like Patan, Shirala, Radhanagari, Wai, Satara and Chandgad are having significant contribution of the potential area for fish farming. Above 80 per cent of area was utilized for stocking the seeds. The rate of stocking was increased upto 1995 by about 7.42 per cent and again remains somewhat constant upto 2000. This rate increased by 0.18 per cent in the year 2002. Due to severe drought after the year of 2002 the rate of utilization of water resources was again decreased. No doubt above 80 per cent of water area is utilised for fish farming but actual water area as compared to the total geographical area in remaining tahsils is not satisfactory. The infrastructural facilities need be strengthened for proper development of fish farming in the region.
