TY  - JOUR
AU  - [Anonymous]
TI  - Managed aquifer recharge applications for climate adaptation in developing countries: mounting evidence, abundant potential.
T2  - IWMI Water Policy Brief
M3  - Bulletin
AB  - This article presents four case studies applying managed aquifer recharge (MAR) with their respective goals and achievements. The first is flood reduction, groundwater level restoration and sustained agricultural productivity in Uttar Pradesh, India, where the Underground Transfer of Floods for Irrigation (UTFI) approach to MAR has increased groundwater storage by over 25,000 m3per year at the pilot scale, and has since been adopted in hundreds of villages in the Ramganga Basin. The second is water security improvement and gender equality in Zimbabwe's Shashe catchment, where sand dams have improved water security by extending water availability by more than 4 months annually and reduced the daily burden of water collection on women, providing them with time to engage in other livelihood activities. Third is flood mitigation and urban water supply improvement in Islamabad, Pakistan, where the installation of 100 MAR sites has fostered recharge of stormwater to mitigate flood risk, raise groundwater levels by over 3 meters and improve water quality. Last is climate adaptation in agriculture in Vietnam's Central Highlands, where MAR has alleviated seasonal water shortages for coffee farmers by capturing monsoonal runoff for groundwater recharge, satisfying up to one-third of irrigation water needs during critical dry season months.
