AU  - Singh, R. K.
AU  - Anamika Singh, Anamika Singh
TI  - Indigenous healthcare practices in vogue among rural women.
T2  - Journal of Medicinal and Aromatic Plant Sciences
M3  - Journal article
AB  - In the present study, an effort was made to explore the diversities of indigenous knowledge systems pertaining to human health among rural women. Respondents and villages of study were selected purposively from eastern part of Azamgarh district, Uttar Pradesh, India. Data pertaining to study were collected by using the participatory approach, group discussions, participant observations and personal interview methods. Results indicate that women have their ancestral wisdom to cure many ailments and diseases. They use various bioresources available locally to mange ailments and diseases. For examples use ofDatura stramonium,Tamarindus indica,Boerhavia diffusa,Blumea balsamiferaD.C.,Amorphophallus campanulatusBlume.,Sirka(fermented sugarcane juice),Aegle marmelos,Acacia niloticaandPhyllanthus amarusare quite popular among them ethnobotanicals which are used against various diseases and ailments. A range of indigenous fruits and tubers are also utilized during drought and food scarcity to meet the need of nutrition and maintain health. These indigenous practices of health were found to be appropriate on account of lower cost, good efficacy and easy local availability.
