TI  - Farmers' constraints, objectives and achievements in smallholder dairy systems in Uganda.
T2  - Livestock Research for Rural Development
M3  - Journal article
AB  - A study was carried out in Masaka district, Uganda, to understand farmers' constraints, objectives and achievements in dairy production. The study was conducted in two phases: an informal cross-sectional survey; and a longitudinal study. A sample of 60 farmers was selected randomly, and a participatory method was used. Farmers had several objectives, which included, paying school fees, daily home maintenance, buying cow requirements (enterprise self sufficiency), increasing soil fertility, home milk consumption and increasing herd value, in order of importance. Generally, farmers achieved the following objectives: improving soil fertility by applying manure, followed by buying cow requirements and home milk consumption. However, the farmers did not fully achieve their most important objective of paying the school fees of their children. The major constraining factors to dairy production were: prolonged drought, which lead to feed scarcity; and the poor milk market.
