AU  - Fajardo, S.
AU  - Kam SuanPheng, Kam SuanPheng
TI  - Natural resource inventory of Luppi village, eastern plateau of India: implications for sustainable agricultural development.
T2  - Journal of Sustainable Agriculture
M3  - Journal article
AB  - This study examined the natural resource inventory of Luppi village, situated in the eastern plateau of India, using a geographic information system, satellite imagery (IRS 1C LISS III satellite imagery) and participatory rural appraisal. A base map and a resource map of the village were developed using GEOMATICA software. Toposequence based micro-level study revealed that there were four types of land situations: tanr (upper terraces), bahri (land close to homesteads), baad (middle terraces), and garha (lower terraces). Adverse bio-physical and socio-economic conditions and age-old, traditional, unscientific agricultural activities in the region act as deterrents for crop production and natural resource management. Based on the study, it can be concluded that priority should be given to long-term strategies encompassing: (i) silviculture or silvi-pastoral systems (cultivation of trees and pasture simultaneously) in the upland areas and cultivation of short-duration, flash-flood tolerant, high-yielding rice variety for aman (wet) season and cold-tolerant rice variety for winter season in lowland areas; (ii) social forestry in degraded land; (iii) agro-ecologically suited cropping systems with suitable variety choice for problem areas; and (iv) judicious nutrient management in homestead gardens that is ecologically suitable, socio-economically acceptable, technologically sound, and environmentally sustainable.
