AU  - Chauhan, Ruchika
AU  - Malik, D. S.
TI  - Impact assessment of cloudbursts on riverine fisheries of Garhwal region, Uttarakhand.
T2  - Journal of Experimental Zoology, India
M3  - Journal article
AB  - Nature has endowed the Garhwal region with a wealth of fast-flowing rivers, lakes and reservoirs including rich flora and fauna. The paper highlights the importance of aquatic biodiversity for ecosystem stability and emphasizes the role of fish as indicators of habitat suitability and ecological health in aquatic systems. The present paper provides valuable information on the impact of cloudbursts on riverine fisheries of different aquatic bodies of Uttarakhand. The effect of cloudbursts reported on river morphology and water characteristics include excessive surface runoff that leads to soil erosion and sedimentation in rivers, which disrupts fish's natural habitats, food spectrum, and spawning sites for breeding grounds. Disturbances such as floods and turbidity affect the availability of food resources for fish, potentially impacting their growth and abundance. The present investigations revealed that the population abundance and fish species richness were drastically changed after cloudburst events on particular rivers of the Garhwal region. Out of the total collected information of 58 cloudburst events that occurred over the past nine years in the Garhwal region, Chamoli district witnessed a staggering count of 20 cloudburst events, marking the highest recorded occurrence among all observed regions. Furthermore, a significant mean reduction of fish diversity (10-25%) and fish biomass (22-30%) has been observed concerning the river biodiversity. The present study may contribute to developing the predicting models for developing mitigation measures to protect the riverine fisheries in terms of increasing climatic variability in the Himalayan region.
