AU  - Nagnur, Shobha
AU  - Kulkarni, V. S.
TI  - Migratory pattern of Deccani sheep rearing families in belagavi district, Karnataka, India.
T2  - Journal of Experimental Zoology, India
M3  - Journal article
AB  - A study was carried out in 2018 to identify the migratory routes of Deccani sheep in Belagavi district (Karnataka, India). A total of 90 migratory Deccani sheep rearing families (90 men and 90 women) were selected by the snowball sampling method. The well-structured pre-tested interview schedules were used to collect primary data. The results revealed that the majority of shepherds (75.56%) follow permanent migration. Cent percent of respondents told that lack of fodder and lack of water are the main reasons to migrate, and the large majority of respondents (85.60%) expressed the lack of land for sheep sheds. An equal percentage (83.30%) of the families expressed drought and lack of grazing land as the reasons. In the present study, two forms of migratory patterns were observed viz. temporary and permanent migration. In temporary migration, the journey starts soon after the end of the monsoon season i.e., during October-November. In permanent migration, shepherds migrate all through the year. They stay in 50-80 villages depending upon the availability of fodder and water. They travel on an average of 12 km daily for grazing sheep around the villages where they have penned the animals. The migratory routes of the shepherds are almost fixed routes. These routes can be identified to plan for grazing lands, feed and fodder, water, extension services, veterinary services, bank facilities, education to children etc.
