TI  - Consumption of livestock products by the women and preschool children in drought prone areas of Anantapur District, Andhra Pradesh.
T2  - Journal of Research ANGRAU
M3  - Journal article
AB  - The consumption pattern of livestock products of women and preschool children from Anantapur District, Andhra Pradesh, India between peak (September-January) and lean (May-July) seasons was compared. A total of 90 families were selected based on landholding size: small, medium, large farm families and landless labour households. Information on consumption pattern was collected by 24-h recall method using a set of standardized diet survey vessels. The intake of milk was significantly lower during lean season as compared to peak season in both women and preschool children. The milk purchased for 50 paise or Rs. 1.00, especially during lean season was mostly given to children and otherwise used for tea. Use of curds was very rare. The intake of milk was significantly lower in lean season over peak period even in women and preschool children of large farm groups. Even the families who were producing the milk were not consuming the required amounts of milk particularly in lean period for want of money to meet the staple shortages. Children were given only tea in place of milk and not given any other milk products especially in lean spells. Milk was much below the requirements in both seasons in both women and preschool children in all categories of families studied. Consumption of fleshy foods and eggs by both women and preschool children in all the farming communities studied was low in both seasons. Very few families occasionally consumed meat and eggs and the diet was almost lacking in meat, fish, egg and chicken. It is concluded that there was no marked difference in the consumption of livestock products between 4 types of families.
