AU  - Chen, Yun-Yan
AU  - Wu, Hua
TI  - Clinical and microbiological characteristics of melioidosis in Ledong, Hainan.
T2  - China Tropical Medicine
M3  - Journal article
AB  - Objective: To provide a scientific basis for diagnosis and treatment of melioidosis by summarizing the clinical and microbiological characteristics of meilioidosis Burkholderia pseudomalleiin Ledong area. Methods: Retrospective analysis was conducted to summarize and analyze the information of melioidosis cases in Ledong Li ethnic minority area, Hainan Province from August 2018 to September 2020. Suspected strains were identified by biochemical reactions, and to those identified as Burkholderia pseudomallei, were re-identified by whole-genome sequencing; Micro broth dilution method was used to detect the susceptibility of Burkholderia pseudomalleito antibiotics. Results: All the 14 melioidosis patients had diabetes; 71.43% showed symptoms between June and September; 78.57% were male; 78.57% were farmers; 71.43% of the patients aged between 50 and 65 years old. Septicemia was the most common clinical manifestations, accounted for 92.86%; Bacteria were cultured for 48 h, the colonies changed from moist, convex to dry, flat, and the bacteria showed dense staining at both ends and light staining in the middle section under the microscope. The biochemical identification of Burkholderia pseudomalleiwas consistent with whole genome sequencing. The pathogen was susceptible to ceftazidime, imipenem, meropenem, and compound sulfamethoxazole. For clinical outcome, 10 cases were cured or improved, 4 were dead, the mortality rate was 28.57%. Conclusion: Melioidosis occurs frequently in the typhoon season. Male diabetic farmers are a high-risk group and are prone to develop sepsis and die. Clinicians, especially primary care doctors, should improve their awareness of melioidosis so as to achieve early detection, early diagnosis, and early treatment.
