TI  - Rice fish horticulture model - an approach to improve the livelihood security in the flood affected areas of Dhemaji district, Assam.
T2  - Environment and Ecology
M3  - Journal article
AB  - An action research project was carried out in Dhemaji district of Assam which is one of the most backward and remotest districts of North Bank Plain Zone of Assam. Due to severe flood the livelihood of people becomes scattered, crops and houses get submerged, health problems become acute and water logging seriously delays and affects the next crop. Deposition of sand due to continuous flood has changed the scenario of livelihood from agriculture to daily wage earner. The objective of this project is to improve the rural livelihood by efficient management of natural resources, capacity building and institutional building of the stakeholders. Rice fish horticulture model was introduced under the project for greater profitability of the farmers from the same resource as they were unable to utilize their land throughout the year because of severe flood situation in monsoon season. The fish along with rice and vegetables were cultured in post flood situation from August to December. There were altogether 30 ha land that has been covered under rice fish hoticulture model and in 35 ha of land covering 259 house holder. In the first year it was observed that the total income was marginally higher than total cost and the average benefit cost ratio was 1.25 as there were fixed costs involved in construction of peripheral trenches in the rice field for fish culture. After completion of second year it was observed that the benefit cost ratio rises to 5.11 and farmers income rises 8.43% than before introduction of the model.
