AU  - Marini Pablo, Roberto
AU  - Chagoya-Fuentes, Jorge Luis
TI  - Effect of the drought season and parity on reproductive performance of dual-purpose cows in tropical conditions.
T2  - Revista Biologico Agropecuaria Tuxpan
M3  - Journal article
AB  - The state of Veracruz has the largest cattle population in Mexico, and most of them are found in dual-purpose systems in tropical conditions where the hot and dry seasons are prolonged. Objective of this research was to determine the effect of temperature and parity on reproductive performance in dual-purpose cows during the dry season. Study was conducted in Tuxpan, Veracruz, and included 50 dual-purpose cows withBos taurus*Bos indicusheterosis. Cows were managed in an intensive tropical pasture rotation system and milked once daily with the calf on the side. Estrus detection was performed twice daily, and service was performed by controlled mating. Additionally, ambient temperature was recorded and classified as low (33.0 to 28.0°C), medium (34.0 to 36.0°C), and high (> 37.0°C). Statistical analysis was performed using Statistica 10 software. Ambient temperature affected fertility (P < 0.05). Cows bred during high temperatures had lower fertility (19.5%) compared to cows bred during medium (41.1%) and low (44.7%) temperatures. Fertility was also affected (P < 0.05) by parity. First-calving cows had higher fertility (37.6%) compared to second-calving cows (33.0%) and those with three or more calvings (26.9%). In conclusion, high temperatures and dry season temperatures and parity affected the fertility of dual-purpose cows under tropical conditions.
