AU  - ,
TI  - Keynote lectures from 28th International Congress on Occupational Health, Milan, Italy, 11-16 June, 2006.
T2  - Medicina del Lavoro
M3  - Journal issue
M3  - Conference proceedings
AB  - This journal contains invited lectures delivered in plenary and semiplenary sessions of the congress. The topics of the lectures are: challenges for occupational health and safety (OHS); workplace stress and strategies to deal with it; aging and globalization; challenge of work force ageing; social protection sustainability, prolongation of working life and greater participation of women in the labour market; occupational inequalities in health; psychological well-being and work attitudes across a range of employment status categories; emerging aspects of psychological risk (violence and harassment at work); longer term health impact of war service; evaluation of scientific evidence in law, adjudication and policy; prioritizing future resources for epidemiologic research on old and newly emerging occupational hazards; work-related musculoskeletal disorders; health risks of exposure to non-ionizing radiation; need for occupational epidemiology in poor countries; epidemiology in risk management for chemicals; refining the focus of construction injury surveillance; recent developments in human biomonitoring (non-invasive assessment of target tissue dose and effects of pneumotoxic metals); association between nurses' age, health and intent to leave the profession; risks of occupational exposure to optical radiation; precautionary options for mobile phone use; development of clinical prediction guides; new structure and contents of employers' juridical responsibility for workers' health and safety in the post-industrial system; integrating occupational health, safety and worksite health promotion; the stress-disequilibrium theory; cardiovascular risk as a consequence of stress at work; relationship between work and cardiovascular disease; flexibility of working hours in the 24-h society; occupational health and general practice; occupational physician and chemical disasters; low-cost risk reduction strategy for small workplaces; contribution of occupational risks to the global burden of disease; toxicogenomics and environmental diseases (search for biomarkers predictive of adverse effects); guidance values for the biomonitoring of occupational exposure to metals; behavioural toxicology; framework for considering genetics in the workplace; harmonized approach to setting OEL's; occupational hygiene; low dose occupational exposure to asbestos and lung cancer risk; CASH (innovative approach to sustainable OSH improvement at workplace); lessons from SARS in an age of emerging infections; globalization outpacing ethics and social responsibility in occupational health; scientific basis of a total asbestos ban; clinical activities, didactics and research in Occupational Medicine; emerging opportunities to prevent occupational lung disease; occupational asthma; indoor air quality and health in offices and other non-industrial working environments; emerging infectious disease; occupational health and safety in agriculture; risk assessment and management of occupational exposure to pesticide in agriculture; and occupational physician in the post-modern world.
