TI  - Characteristics and performance of fisheries co-management in Asia; synthesis of knowledge and case studies: Bangladesh, Cambodia, Philippines, and Sri Lanka.
T2  - Characteristics and performance of fisheries co-management in Asia. Synthesis of knowledge and case studies: Bangladesh, Cambodia, Philippines and Sri Lanka
M3  - Miscellaneous
AB  - The overarching objective of this study is to draw up a series of recommendations for fisheries management agencies in Asia. To do this it draws lessons from published reports and in-depth case studies in Bangladesh, Cambodia, Philippines, and Sri Lanka to understand whether these best practice principles, such as equitable participation, transparency, and empowerment, are translated into best practice as co-management is applied. The recommendations are intended to improve how co-management is used, so that it will ultimately lead to better and more equitable social, ecological and economic outcomes. In sum, co-management arrangements for fisheries are widespread, diverse, dynamic and supported by a range of institutional structures and organisations. The impacts and outcomes associated with fisheries co-management are generally positive across a range of social, ecological and governance measures. However, despite the presence of co-management, fisheries systems (in terms of the people, the natural systems and the institutions they involve) are subject to a range of pressures and influencing factors that act at a scale beyond the effective reach or influence of co-management. A range of measures can be implemented to build more supportive policy and institutional environments that would enable effective, inclusive, robust and widespread co-management. Implementing these measures would, in general, lie within the scope, capacity and mandate of fisheries agencies. In addition, government agencies (fisheries agencies, but importantly also those agencies that manage agriculture, health, disaster response, water, rural development etc.) need to remain responsive to external or macro-level drivers (environmental, social, political and demographic) that are beyond the sphere of influence or sphere of control of fisheries co-management and co-managers. Addressing these drivers so that fisheries remain viable and productive, fishing communities are food secure and experience well-being, and natural environments remain sustainable, will require that governments invest further in intersectoral responses (i.e. multiple government departments working in a more coordinated way) and also increase government accountability downwards - towards fishing communities, fishers, and the women and men who work in fisheries value chains.
