TI  - The newOtor: risk management in a desert grassland.
T2  - Restoring community connections to the land: building resilience through community-based rangeland management in China and Mongolia
M3  - Book chapter
AB  - Drought is one of the biggest threats to animal husbandry in Inner Mongolia, and otor and surug were the two main strategies to cope with serious droughts. Otor describes the practice of moving the herd to better grasslands in response to unfavourable or drought conditions. Surug, in contrast, was a system in which herders facing difficult conditions leased a core number of their young female animals to herders who were not as affected by the unfavourable conditions; when the grasslands recovered, the original herders took back their livestock. This paper describes the series of investigations conducted in typical pastoral areas of Sonid Left Banner, launching a community-based grassland management project in Sonid Left Banner to explore the role of herders' cooperatives in grassland management. Sonid Left Banner is located in the northwest of Xilingol League, Inner Mongolia, on the south-eastern part of the Mongolian Plateau. Results have provided new understandings of what is needed to successfully establish a cooperative in China's pastoral regions, the opportunities created by these cooperatives and the challenges they face.
