AU  - Sami, Abel
AU  - Koran, Douglas
TI  - Reflecting on four years of community-based fisheries management development in Vanuatu.
T2  - SPC Fisheries Newsletter
M3  - Journal article
AB  - Since 2017, the Vanuatu Department of Fisheries (VFD) has been collaborating with partners to implement its component of a regional project to strengthen community-based fisheries management (CBFM). Known as the Pathways Project, its overall aim is to improve the wellbeing of men, women and children in coastal communities through more productive and resilient fisheries, and better food and nutrition security. Five outcome briefs are presented for five action areas of the project. The first brief presets an account of the project's efforts to strengthen CBFM institutions, highlighting national policy impacts and impacts on management practices in communities. The second brief presents capacity development initiatives that were undertaken for VFD staff. It focuses on capacity building areas of gender-sensitive CBFM and nutrition-based management, as well as regional professional networking initiatives allowing knowledge and skills exchange among officers. The third brief reflects on innovative strategies that were developed with partners for improving how CBFM information gets disseminated to coastal communities. The fourth brief presents several programmes that were developed to improve the collection, management and application of data as part of national monitoring efforts. It highlights, in particular, VFD's uptake of a solar-powered freezer monitoring programme that was piloted by the project. Finally, the fifth brief reports on measures taken to quickly mobilise resources, funding and technical advice in support of disaster relief efforts, also underlining the importance of CBFM in improving the resilience of coastal communities.
