TI  - Herbage production during drought in silvopastoral systems on a rocky rangeland in arid zone of India.
T2  - Annals of Arid Zone
M3  - Journal article
AB  - A study on herbage production in silvopastoral systems on rocky rangeland, Bhopalgarh, conducted during drought years 1999 and 2000 with five tree and two shrub species at 14 and 15 year of age revealed that average air dried herbage yield in the inter spaces (10*4 m) of different silvopastures was lowest withDichrostachys nutans(620 kg ha-1) compared to other silvopastoral systems as well as pasture without trees exceptAcacia tortilis(804 kg ha-1).Acacia tortilisshowed maximum survival (96.66%) and growth in height (4.86 m), collar diameter (16.3 cm), dbh (11.03 cm) and canopy diameter (6.63 m). The survival percentage ofAcacia SenegalandD. nutanswas 81.66 and 78.33%, respectively, which showed that 3 MPTS viz.,A. tortilis,Acacia SenegalandD. nutanswere found better establishing on rocky rangeland. Among theseA. Senegalwas most suitable for long term silvopasture. Leaf fodder yield was maximum inD. nutans(8.89 kg tree-1) followed byAzadirachta indica(6.50 kg tree-1),A. tortilis(5.00 kg tree-1) andA. Senegal(4.95 kg tree-1), while fuel wood yield was highest inA. tortilis(68.00 kg tree-1). A comparison of weather parameters during good rainfall years with that of drought years (1999 and 2000) revealed that during drought years, the air temperatures were higher by 0.8°C, relative humidity was lower by 4% and duration of bright sunshine hours increased by 0.3 hr day-1resulting in higher evaporation rates by 1.5 mm day-1. The study on impact of drought showed that the decline in herbage production was highest inD. nutans(65%) followed byAzadirachta indica(57%),A. Senegal(54%),Hardwarckia binata(52%),Colophospermum mopane(51%),A. tortilis(49%),Albizia lebbek(48%) and in sole grass without tree (47%).
