AU  - Ganesh Chandra, Ganesh Chandra
TI  - Impact of adoption of pen culture technology on well-being of fishers of Haribhanga wetland in Assam.
T2  - Indian Research Journal of Extension Education
M3  - Journal article
AB  - This study examines the impact of technology intervention on the production and productivity of floodplain wetlands in Haribhanga Beel, Nagaon district, Assam, India and the consequent improvement on the well-being of the fishers. A survey was conducted on sixty-four fisher families. An impact pathway was developed for the study. After the adoption of pen culture technology, annual fish production of the wetland increased significantly from 37000 kg in 2002-03 to 131250 kg in 2006-07. Productivity also increased from 296 kg ha-1 yr-1 in 2002-03 to 1050 kg ha-1 yr-1. Apart from the increase in the income of lessee, there was substantial increase in the income of other fishers. The cost benefit ratio of fisheries in the Haribhanga beel was 3.23. The direct impact of adoption of CIFRI technology was manifested in the increase of fish production and productivity of the floodplain wetlands, which directly helped in raising the income of the fisher household and livelihood security. The indirect impact of adoption of this technology can be seen in the increase of total fish productivity from the wetlands and increase in the per capita fish availability in the state. This impact study also provided the information on the technology profitability and its effect on household income.
